            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kian Rashidi\u2019s understanding of hospitality was born not in a classroom, but in his family\u2019s Fremont market. The son of Iranian immigrants from Shiraz, he grew up watching his parents treat every customer with a profound sense of welcome, where offering a sample of pistachios or a cup of tea was a gesture of genuine connection. While they instilled in him the value of hard work and education, Kian absorbed the art of hosting.\n\nHe initially pursued a practical business degree, but a post-graduation trip through Andalusia, Spain, became his pivotal turning point. In the sherry bodegas and lively tapas bars, he saw how beverages could be the centerpiece of community and culture. This revelation led him to Cornell University, where he earned an MBA in Hospitality Management, determined to merge his inherited sense of grace with high-level strategy.\n\nKian built his career methodically, working as a sommelier in Napa before taking on management roles in San Francisco. He leveraged his expertise to become the Beverage Director for a critically-acclaimed Hayes Valley restaurant, a role that perfectly suits his meticulous nature and creative palate.\n\nNow at 38, Kian\u2019s life is woven into the fabric of his neighborhood. His 1.5-mile walk to work is a cherished ritual, a time to observe the city's rhythm before the controlled chaos of evening service begins. His days involve tasting sessions with vintners, training staff on obscure amari, and collaborating with the chef to create perfect pairings. While his demanding schedule makes long-term relationships challenging, he maintains a close-knit circle of industry friends who understand the demanding lifestyle.\n\nKian\u2019s connection to San Francisco is both professional and deeply personal; he curates experiences for the city's residents nightly. His ultimate dream is to open his own establishment in the neighborhood\u2014not a splashy nightclub, but a small, intimate bar dedicated to unique spirits and impeccable service. It would be a modern homage to the lessons learned in his parents' market: a place built on exquisite taste and the simple, powerful art of making a guest feel truly seen."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was eight, hiding behind the high counter of his parents' Fremont market. A woman, new to the neighborhood and looking overwhelmed, hesitated by the nuts. He watched his father approach, not with a sales pitch, but with a warm smile and a small handful of pistachios. The woman's anxious face softened into a grateful one. It wasn't a transaction; it was a welcome. That quiet, generous gesture became Kian\u2019s foundational understanding of what it meant to truly host someone.\n\n2.\nHe was 22, sitting alone in a dusty, dimly lit sherry bodega in Jerez. He watched the old bartender use a *venencia*, a special ladle, to draw a stream of amber liquid from a cask, arcing it perfectly into a glass. The reverence in the room was palpable. At that moment, his practical business degree felt like a suit that didn't fit. This\u2014the history, the ritual, the community created from a single beverage\u2014was the language he was meant to speak. It set his life on a new course.\n\n3.\nAt 32, the city\u2019s notoriously severe food critic was at the chef\u2019s table. The chef sent out a challenging, gamey squab. Ignoring his manager's suggestion for a safe Burgundy, Kian poured an obscure, earthy Aglianico he had fought to get on the list. The critic took a bite, then a sip, paused, and gave Kian a slow, deliberate nod of approval. That silent acknowledgment was a surge of pure validation, cementing his confidence in his own palate over commercial appeal.\n\n4.\nJust last winter, walking his usual route home after a brutal 14-hour shift, he passed the windows of other bars. Through the rain-streaked glass, he saw the laughter and connection he worked so hard to create for others. A profound wave of loneliness washed over him\u2014the feeling of being the architect of a party he could never truly attend. It wasn't self-pity, but a clarifying ache that sharpened his desire to build a small haven he could finally call his own.\n\n5.\nDuring a visit home last year, he saw his father, now moving a little slower, talking to a customer. Almost unconsciously, his dad reached into a bin, broke open a dried fig, and offered a piece. The gesture was so ingrained, so full of an ageless grace, that Kian felt a lump form in his throat. His dream for his own bar suddenly clicked into focus. It wasn't just a career move; it was a legacy\u2014a way to honor the simple, powerful inheritance from his father's hands."
